<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written submission from That’s Electric! Ltd</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:18pt 0pt 4.5pt 36pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-36pt"><a name="_Toc369879833"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written submission from That’s Electric! Ltd </span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I have just watched the televised recording of last week’s meeting and cannot quite make up my mind as to the best description for it – ‘car crash TV’ or ‘Four desperadoes trying to wrestle control of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> the gravy train before it departs them forever’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Whilst I am largely in favour of this government’s aims to reduce bureaucracy and encourage healthy competition, if ever there was a clear example of where the State needs to step in to control a situation </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">before it becomes too desperate between competing factions then this is it.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Please allow me a few brief moments of your time to outline my thoughts.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">By way of introduction, I am an experienced (20+ years) electrician and employer, typical of many of the th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ousands of small businesses and/or sole trader tradesman currently under discussion in this process, working both locally, nationally and on occasions internationally.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">It is this latter reference to international work which I hold most dear – at one time, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">the United Kingdom was very much a technical leader and historically had developed protocols and methods which have been adopted world-wide with an electrical safety record to rival – if not better – any other nation. Sadly, today I could not be sure of su</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ch a claim.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">“Part P”, to use the informal terminology, was – on paper – a reasonably good idea. A way to create a base line so that the homeowner could expect certain standards and the Government a level of public protection. Unfortunately, the method empl</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">oyed has fallen extremely short of doing either and has become a little more than a futile white elephant. All it seems to have created is a confused landscape with little advancement in quality save for the pension schemes of those in front of you last we</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ek, which I wouldn’t ordinarily mind except for the simple fact that it’s my money, and that of my hard working colleagues up and down the land that is lining them, and for no good reason or return on investment.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">To put some context to this – on an annual </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">basis it costs me, as a business, around £1500 just simply to be ‘open’. This is made up of the fees to these organisations (whichever one you choose), the mandatory insurances, various other fees for technical issues, constant requirements for professiona</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">l development and so on. Add in all the other more normal running costs of a business and it is no wonder that we cannot compete against the black market that now exists. If the public still has a perception of the ‘raking it in’ tradesman then this is now</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> very much unfounded as far as an average electrician is concerned. Indeed, a few minutes spent searching around the internet will easily tell you why any young person with the academic ability to undertake an old-style conventional apprenticeship such as </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I enjoyed will also have the intelligence to realise that there are far more profitable career options available to them within fare less demanding forms of employment.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Should their choice not work out, then they can always re-enter the trade at a later da</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">te simply by signing away their credit rating to a variety of fast-track training short-cuts, payment of fees to the schemes above and so on.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">It is of primary note that these fast-track courses DID NOT EXIST BEFORE PART P, and that the basic qualifications</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> that they create are the ones which have been most relied on by the various schemes to meet their own ends.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">For example, the NICEIC, which was once a ‘champion of standards’ have the following minimum academic entry criteria – to hold City and Guilds exam</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> 2382, otherwise known as ‘17</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> editions’. Again, to put this into context, this is an online, interactive, multiple choice exam which is open book and consists of 40 questions. In short, you have roughly three and a half minutes to look up the right answe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">r and my dog could pass it. The schemes then seek to ‘safeguard’ this entry criteria by using the process of annual inspection.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">As someone whose own business has been subject to this same annual inspection for the last few years let me leave you in no doub</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">t whatsoever that it is a farce. As the appointed ‘Qualified Supervisor’ for my own business I think I was on site for less than four minutes with our assessor last time.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">There is another organisation largely silent in all of this – the JIB (Joint Industry</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> Board) – who concern themselves less with domestic level electrical work and more with safeguarding standards of traditional level apprentice trained electricians in industry. You will not meet their entry criteria as ‘qualified and/or experienced’ based </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">on the expectations of the others, in fact the ‘core’ qualifications wanted by the schemes are considered little more than periphery add-ons to a solid, safe, understanding of the subject underpinned by proper long-term college training.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Let’s not kid ours</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">elves – electricity kills people and starts roughly 20-25% of all domestic fires (depending on whose figures you read).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">So, to sum up, why will it be that these various organisations will never see a consensus? Because put simply to do so will show their </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">own inadequacies and failings, highlight the staggering amount of corporate greed (however it gets wrapped up in ‘not for profit’ this, that or the other) and frankly show them up as being useless to either the public, government or trade. I would venture </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">so far as to suggest that some of the things you heard last week are most charitably put as distortions of the real truth and have no reality on the streets.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I would please ask you to imagine a United Kingdom where there were competing organisations for su</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ch things as the General Medical Council, Bar Council, DVLA…and so on. We would quickly descend into a place I don’t think either or us, nor the common man, would wish for.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Accepting that the government has not timetabled further discussion on the wider aspects of Part P since the last consultation, I would respectfully suggest that time be called on this fiasco; they’ve had almost a decade of squabbling over the pie and achi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">eved nothing except a lowering of standards. In place should be a Government endorsed compulsory register, much along the lines of GasSafe or any number of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">other countries with similar schemes, with entry requirement dictated by a committee of the IET (it </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">is after all, their own regulations aka BS7671 which we work to), with a monetary system fairly balanced against true running costs and suitably policed by law (else what point is there?).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">Otherwise, some of the horrors I have personally witnessed whilst o</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">verseas may well start to make an appearance on a street near us, and I fear may already have arrived. In fact, I know they have – I’ve seen them already. Who would you prefer to work in your own home and keep your family safe? A rhetorical question I know</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">I would, of course, be more than happy to place my time and opinion at your future disposal should you feel it beneficial, and can only hope that I am not alone in formally voicing my concerns.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>